Here is the complete, streamlined roadmap for your ClamAV setup from start to finish. Since you already ran some of these commands, you can use this as a master checklist or a clean guide if you ever need to set it up again.



##  Complete ClamAV Setup & Automation Guide

### Step 1: Install the Software

Pull the core ClamAV packages from the repositories:


sudo pacman -S clamav



### Step 2: Initialize and Automate the Database

Download the initial virus signatures and hand the daily updates over to a background service:


# 1. Download the signature databases manually
sudo freshclam

# 2. Enable the automatic background update service
sudo systemctl enable --now clamav-freshclam.service



### Step 3: Configure and Start the Daemon Engine (`clamd`)

Configure ClamAV to run as a permanent background service so it keeps definitions loaded in RAM for lightning-fast scanning.

1. Open the configuration file:

sudo nano /etc/clamav/clamd.conf






2. Find the `LocalSocket` rule, ensure it is only written **once**, and that the `#` comment symbol is removed:
   text
   LocalSocket /run/clamav/clamd.ctl



3. Save and exit (`Ctrl + O`, `Enter`, `Ctrl + X`).
4. Enable and fire up the main scanning service:

sudo systemctl enable --now clamav-daemon.service









## 🕒 Step 4: Set Up Automated Nightly Scans (2:00 AM)

### 1. The Script
Create the background automated script:

sudo nano /usr/local/bin/clamdscan-system.sh



Paste this logic inside, then save and exit:


#!/bin/
LOGFILE="/var/log/clamav/daily_scan.log"
echo "=== Scan Started: $(date) ===" >> "$LOGFILE"
clamdscan --fdpass --infected --multiscan --log="$LOGFILE" /home/kaz /usr/bin /usr/local/bin
echo "=== Scan Finished: $(date) ===" >> "$LOGFILE"



Make it executable:


sudo chmod +x /usr/local/bin/clamdscan-system.sh



### 2. The Systemd Service Unit

Create the systemd service to manage the script execution:


sudo nano /etc/systemd/system/clamav-scan.service



Paste this block inside, then save and exit:

ini
[Unit]
Description=Trigger multi-threaded ClamAV system scan
After=clamav-daemon.service

[Service]
Type=simple
ExecStart=/usr/local/bin/clamdscan-system.sh



### 3. The Systemd Timer Schedule

Create the timer to schedule the execution:


sudo nano /etc/systemd/system/clamav-scan.timer



Paste this block inside, then save and exit:

ini
[Unit]
Description=Run ClamAV Scan Automatically

[Timer]
OnCalendar=*-*-* 02:00:00
Persistent=true

[Install]
WantedBy=timers.target



### 4. Activate the Automation Loop

Reload the system services and enable your new timer layout:


sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl enable --now clamav-scan.timer





##  Step 5: Set Up the Manual On-Demand Terminal Command

To have a simple command you can fire off by hand whenever you feel like running a scan, follow these steps:

1. Create the manual utility file:

sudo nano /usr/local/bin/sys-scan






2. Paste this exact fixed code inside, then save and exit:
   
   #!/bin/
   echo "========================================="
   echo "   Starting Manual ClamAV System Scan    "
   echo "========================================="
   echo "Scanning: /home/kaz, /usr/bin, /usr/local/bin"
   echo "Please wait..."
   echo ""

   clamdscan --fdpass --multiscan /home/kaz /usr/bin /usr/local/bin

   echo ""
   echo "========================================="
   echo "             Scan Complete               "
   echo "========================================="



3. Mark it as executable:

sudo chmod +x /usr/local/bin/sys-scan







Now, anytime you want to check your system, simply drop into your terminal shell and run:

sys-scan

